<HL>
   Technology:
   Washington Post Co. Agrees to Finance
   Experimental Wireless-Phone System
   ----
   By John J. Keller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   WPO
</CO>
<IN>
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Washington Post Co., an early investor in the
cellular-phone industry, agreed to finance an experimental
wireless communications system that one day could rival
existing phone services.
   The agreement calls for Washington Post to set up a
limited partnership with Baltimore-based American Personal
Communications Inc., which earlier this year received
licenses from the Federal Communications Commission to build
and test the system in the Washington area.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In addition, Washington Post will invest $6 million to be
used for "research, technology exploration and labor costs
over a two-to-three-year period," said Wayne Schelle, APC's
chairman.
   If the test is successful, the partners said they will ask
the FCC for an operating license to provide service in the
Washington area and will pursue licenses for other U.S.
markets.
   Like cellular networks, the new network will use
transceivers placed around the city to transmit and relay
calls. However, the new system is expected to require far
less electricity than cellular systems. This, proponents say,
will allow for phones that are lighter than current cellular
portables, because their batteries are smaller.
   Mr. Schelle's network is still experimental. But if such
networks test successfully, analysts have said, they could
pose a serious long-term challenge not only to cellular-phone
networks, which provide portable phone services today, but
also to local phone companies that have long enjoyed a
monopoly on hard-wired residential and business phone
services.
   Mr. Schelle envisions a phone that will sell for about $75
once full-scale networks are operating, plus a monthly
service charge of $35 to $45 a month by 1995. Portable
cellular phones, by contrast, sell for $1,000, and service
costs about $90 to $100 a month. Mr. Schelle and Washington
Post were partners in the Washington-Baltimore area's first
cellular network in 1983. He ended up selling his 40%
interest the following year for $52.5 million. The Post left
the cellular business in 1986, realizing a $200 million
after-tax gain on its investment in properties that also
included networks in Detroit and Miami.
   "This gives us a successful partner with sufficient
resources," Mr. Schelle said. "It's like starting the game in
the fourth inning." A spokesman for the Post said the company
will set up a new division to provide and market pocketphone
services if the Washington tests succeed.
   "We're not a company that likes to flip assets," he said.
"Our aim is to do this broadly and systematically in a way in
which we can have a sizable stance."
   The Post is not alone. A growing number of companies are
either planning or have begun to erect networks that will
provide pocketphone services. In England, several companies
already provide a service called Personal Communications
Network, or PCN, that allows customers to place calls on
pocketphones. And several companies, including partnerships
involving regional Bell companies, have begun building
networks in England to provide two-way phone services.
   In the U.S. the FCC has awarded about 20 licenses to test
"personal communications services" or PCS. Companies such as
APC, Millicom Inc. and Graphic Scanning Corp., have received
permission from the FCC to test their PCS systems at various
frequencies.
   Nynex Corp. recently announced plans to install an adjunct
pocketphone-type system to its cellular network, using
network equipment from American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. and
Qualcomm Inc.
   Motorola Inc. plans a satellite-based service. The company
wants to offer portable-phone service through a network of
more than 70 low-orbit satellites by the end of the decade.
   The Post and APC expect to begin testing the system by
year end and to have it working fully in suburban Maryland
and Virginia by the end of 1991.
   The Washington test will involve transmission and
reception in two frequencies -- 900 MHz, which current
cellular networks use, and 1800-1900 MHz, Mr. Schelle said.
   In the first stage, as many as 2,000 customers will get a
one-way service, with which they can place calls after
receiving a message on an attached pager. In the second
stage, expected to be available by the end of next year,
customers will get two-way service allowing them to send and
receive calls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900823-0091
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900823-0091.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Saudis' Oil Riches
   Make Costs of Crisis
   Much Easier to Bear
   ---
   Boost in Output of 2 Million
   Barrels a Day Appears
   Simple -- and Lucrative
   ----
   By John J. Fialka
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   DAMMAM, Saudi Arabia -- Fifty rifle-carrying Bedouins
wearing thick bandoliers of ammunition snap to attention as
Prince Muhammed bin Fahd walks into the arena-size sitting
room of his palace.
   The prince is governor of Saudi Arabia's Eastern Province,
currently overrun with some 100,000 refugees from Kuwait. A
growing chunk of the U.S. military also is encamped here
along the west coast of the Persian Gulf. The Saudis must
provide tank-carrying trucks, troop-carrying buses and much
other logistical support to help the U.S. soldiers defend the
oil fields, if need be, against an attack by Iraq.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A few miles away, in Dhahran, engineers for the
government-owned Saudi Arabian Oil Co. are working out ways
to pump an extra two million barrels of oil a day, crude that
will be desperately needed to ease the shock threatening the
world's economy if the Persian Gulf crisis continues. They
are confident that if ordered to do so, they could do it
quickly.
   The Eastern Province, home of some two million Saudis,
amounts to a company town and, one way or another, the
company -- Saudi Aramco -- is going to take care of the
prince's problems.
   Who will buy gas masks, asks a group of Western reporters,
invited to watch the prince hold court? Who will house and
feed the Kuwaitis? "The government is taking care of that,"
he responds.
   According to Western experts, the government can well
afford to solve the problems, for the crisis has kicked up
the price of oil by more than $10 a barrel. If it decides to
pump the additional oil, the Saudi government will bring in
an extra $100 million a day, they say.
   The mood here is definitely bullish. "We support you with
our blood," says a Kuwaiti supplicant, one of a long line of
turbaned men waiting to hand the prince a petition seeking
help.
   The lifeblood of the Eastern Province is crude and there
is a stupefyingly large amount of it. For example, Prince
Fahd's court sits on Dammam field, an oil formation
containing more than a billion barrels. It has been closed
for several years because the Saudis no longer needed to pump
it.
   The Saudi government has assured the Bush administration
and a number of other oil-thirsty countries that it will
produce the extra oil needed to help them through the crisis,
although the formal announcement will come after further
negotiations with other oil-producing states.
   "It will take some time, but if told to do it in a hurry,
we have tremendous flexibility," explains Sidney D. Bowers,
consultant to Saudi Aramco and formerly chief geologist for
the company when it was owned by four U.S. oil companies.
   During the past two years the company has discovered six
oil fields, most of them containing more than a billion
barrels apiece. It has 53 others, including the fabled Ghawar
field, an underground lake of petroleum that is 160 miles
long and 20 miles wide. In all, there are some 257 billion
barrels of proven reserves here, 25% of the world's supply.
   Mr. Bowers points out that the U.S. has only two oil
fields containing more than a billion barrels and that most
of the U.S. oil comes from fields that are on the verge of
old age.
   "These {Saudi} fields are so good that they're in what we
call a juvenile state," he adds, noting that they provide
plenty of pressure to pump the oil. While production costs in
older fields in the U.S. and elsewhere can run well beyond
$20 a barrel, the Saudis are believed to pump oil at a
maximum cost of about $2 a barrel.
   While the economics for the extra effort are in place, the
social strain of the crisis is beginning to wear on Saudi
Aramco. So far, according to company officials, it has sent
home 3,000 dependents of its expatriate workers, many of them
Americans. Only about 1% of its 11,000 foreign workers have
left, they add.
   Mr. Bowers points out that the company has surged to meet
bigger crises before. In 1977, when a fire knocked out six
million barrels of daily production in one field, oil workers
jury-rigged pumping systems from other fields to make up the
shortfall in a month.
   In those days the company, then called Arabian-American
Oil Co., or Aramco, pumped almost twice the 5.3 million
barrels that it pumps today. Falling oil prices, starting in
1980, forced production cutbacks and sent the economy of the
Eastern Province into a 10-year recession.
   The invasion of Kuwait has ended that and has graphically
underscored the long interdependence between the U.S. and
Saudi Arabia that began one day in 1933 when Max Steineke, a
stubborn geologist for Standard Oil Co. of California, saw a
peculiar, dome-shaped hill near here and had a hunch there
was oil in it.
   Four years and four dry holes later, he had experienced
multiple cave-ins, many broken drill bits and the deep
despair of a Westerner who has spent too much time in the
desert. "No oil, no water," he said in one terse message to
California.
   His fifth well, the following year, brought in the Dammam
field.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900823-0090
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900823-0090.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Have You Heard the New Slogan?
   Join the Party and See the World
   ----
   By Dana Milbank
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<LP>
   PITTSBURGH -- The local Republican Party still may not win
elections, but at least now it offers a winning ticket.
   The woebegone county GOP, outnumbered by Democrats 2 1/2
to 1, has a new scheme to register Republican voters. How
will it combat the electoral imbalance? Fiery rhetoric?
Grass-roots appeal? A heavy dose of idealism?
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "An exciting contest," proposes county GOP Chairman Henry
Sneath, in a letter to fellow Republicans. He wants local
youths to compete in registering Republican voters in
Pennsylvania's 18th Congressional District. The winner will
be selected in a raffle.
   The grand prize: "An all-expense-paid weekend for two to
Washington, D.C." But for those drooling for a trip to the
Potomac, there's a catch: The tightfisted GOP will only pay
$50 each for the winner and guest, including transportation
and hotel.
   The lucky couple will be chaperoned the entire weekend by
doting party elders who will save airfare by driving them on
the five-hour trek. The winner's discount hotel room will be
paid for with leftover frequent flier mileage. And if you're
going with your sweetheart, you may have to sleep in separate
rooms, says Sallie Duhon, a 55-year-old ward coordinator who
will chaperone the trip.
   "It's not the fanciest trip," admits Rick Santorum, the
Republican candidate for the 18th District. There may be no
free lunch in Washington, but county Republicans hope party
fat cats in the capital will pick up part of the tab.
   When the 18th District, in suburban Pittsburgh, was
redrawn in 1981, it gave the GOP a chance to gain a
congressional seat. But the Republicans still haven't won it,
nor do they hold any of the other four seats in Southwestern
Pennsylvania.
   Some 25 eager young Republicans have signed on, but the
target of the registration drive, Democratic incumbent Doug
Walgren, hasn't let the extravaganza disrupt his New England
vacation. Says Jonathan Delano, Mr. Walgren's chief of staff:
"No one is quaking in their boots."
   One Republican volunteer, David Rice, 21, says he wasn't
lured by the prize. "I don't see how you could be," he says.
   Maybe that's because he hasn't heard about the "attractive
runner-up prizes." These include tickets for the Republican
"victory cruise" on the Allegheny River. The party has high
hopes for the election, but apparently not too high: The
cruise sails three weeks before Election Day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
