<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
08/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   CRUDE OIL PRICES passed the $30-a-barrel mark, their
highest level since the early 1980s. The Mideast turmoil also
pushed up prices of refined petroleum in frantic trading.
Gasoline futures rose nearly three cents a gallon. Oil
industry officials reported tightening supplies of some
products in certain countries.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stocks and bonds fell sharply on the surge in oil prices.
The Treasury's 30-year bond fell more than a point, pushing
its yield above 9%. The Dow Jones industrials fell 43.81
points. Broad stock indexes hit their lowest points in more
than a year. The dollar closed mostly lower.
   ---
   Gold prices climbed further on the Mideast crisis. The
December futures contract gained $3.30 an ounce.
   ---
   Tokyo stock prices plunged amid anxiety about the Mideast.
The Nikkei marked a post-1987 low before closing down 1086.93
points. The index fell 1,003.96 points Thursday morning.
                                                                                                       

   Long-term Japanese market sentiment has turned bearish due
to a liquidity squeeze, say analysts.
   ---
   Electrolux plans to lay off 10% of its 150,000 workers
world-wide in a cost-cutting move. The Swedish appliance
concern said the biggest cuts would come in the U.S. The
firm's second-period pretax profit fell 56%.
   ---
   Banks are concerned about an obscure federal law that lets
members of the U.S. armed forces reduce the rates they pay on
consumer loans.
   ---
   Donald Trump took his shuttle airline off the market hours
after he signed the final papers on his $65 million bank
bailout. The developer said the airline is now profitable.
   ---
   The NASD's effort to expand its trading system into London
has hit a regulatory snag over reporting requirements. The
project could be delayed or even scuttled.
   ---
   Money market fund assets rose $6.5 billion in the latest
week to a record $400.4 billion as both individuals and
institutions sought safety.
   ---
   National Intergroup agreed to put up for sale its only
operating business, wholesale drug distributor FoxMeyer,
caving in to the demands of dissident holder Centaur
Partners.
   ---
   A CBS News shake-up appears imminent, and may result in
the ouster of the unit's president, David Burke.
   ---
   CrossLand Savings' plan to meet new capital requirements
was rejected by federal regulators.
   ---
   Washington Post Co. agreed to finance an experimental
wireless-communications system that would use lightweight
portable phones. The venture could compete with existing
cellular and traditional phone services.
   ---
   RJR's $6.9 billion refinancing is being challenged in
court on grounds that it is unfair to bondholders.
   ---
   Stocks: Volume 175,550,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2560.15, off 43.81; transportation 894.34, off 14.24;
utilities 196.81, off 1.69.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3305.18, off
31.69.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.33, up 0.30; spot
index 133.06, up 0.02.
   Dollar: 146.30 yen, off 0.35; 1.5590 marks, off 0.0055.
</TEXT>
