   International Brief -- Arabian Oil Co.:
   Tokyo Firm's Pretax Profit
   Slipped 1.4% in First Half
</HL>
<DATE>
08/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Arabian Oil Co., Japan's biggest oil producer, reported
that its unconsolidated pretax profit in the first half of
fiscal 1990 slipped 1.4% to 27.87 billion yen ($190.1
million) from 28.25 billion yen the year earlier.
   Although sales rose 1% in the half ended June 30,
operating profit at the Tokyo company was down 1.5% to 28.07
billion yen from 28.5 billion yen. As a result, net income
fell to 1.12 billion, down 2.6% from 1.15 billion yen the
year earlier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Per-share earnings inched down to 21.59 yen from 22.72
yen. Sales volume fell 12% to 6.7 million kiloliters. But the
value of sales rose to 94.78 billion yen from 93.87 billion
yen.
